      <div class="page-header">
        <h1>What Gerrymandering Looks Like In Court</h1>
        <p class="subtitle">Past court cases that have set precedents the future of gerrymandering.</p>
      </div>


      <div class="accordion" data-type="single">
        <div class="accordion-item open">
          <button class="accordion-header">
            <div class="acc-subtitle-row">Rucho v. Common Cause (2019)</div>
            <svg class="acc-arrow" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg>
          </button>
          <div class="accordion-body"><div class="accordion-body-inner">
            <p>In 2019, <i>Rucho v. Common Cause</i> debated amongst the Supreme Court whether the partisan gerrymandering in Maryland and North Carolina was fair. </p>
            <p>In a 5-4 decision, the court did in fact state that partisan gerrymandering was "incompatible with democratic principles." However, they still decided in the majority opinion that the oversight of partisan gerrymandering was out of the interpretation of federal law, i.e., the Supreme Court could not challenge the gerrymander in either state.</p>
            <p>This case set a precedent for the future that the federal government could not control partisan gerrymanders.</p>
          </div></div>
        </div>

        <div class="accordion-item">
          <button class="accordion-header">
            <div class="acc-subtitle-row">Thornburg v. Gingles (1986)</div>
            <svg class="acc-arrow" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg>
          </button>
          <div class="accordion-body"><div class="accordion-body-inner">
            <p><i>Thornburg v. Gingles</i> was a Supreme Court case that handled racial gerrymandering and the <strong>Voting Rights Act of 1965</strong>. Black voters in North Carolina argued that the gerrymandering in North Carolina was racist and prevented equal suffrage.</p>
            <p>The Supreme Court ruled in their favor, stating that the gerrymandering goes against Section 2 of the Voting Rights Act which bans racial discrimination in elections.</p>
            <p>This case set the precedent that the Supreme Court could oversee state gerrymanders as long as it was a racial gerrymander (which would later be contrasted by partisan gerrymanders in <i>Rucho v. Common Cause</i>).</p>
          </div></div>
        </div>

        <div class="accordion-item">
          <button class="accordion-header">
            <div class="acc-subtitle-row">Shaw v. Reno (1993)</div>
            <svg class="acc-arrow" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg>
          </button>
          <div class="accordion-body"><div class="accordion-body-inner">
            <p><i>Shaw v. Reno</i> handled a similar topic as <i>Thornburg v. Gingles</i>, where white voters argued that North Carolina's 1990 districting violated the <strong>14th Amendment</strong>. North Carolina actually originally intended the districts to adhere to the <strong>Voting Rights Act of 1965</strong>, giving minority groups advantaged voting. However, it ended up backfiring when white voters became packed into districts.</p>
            <p>In a 5-4 ruling, the Supreme Court noted that even though North Carolina was helping minority voters, redistricting based on race is unconstitutional. This court case established that when race is the primary factor in redistricting, <strong>strict scrutiny</strong> is applied.</p>
          </div></div>
        </div>
      </div>

